```

The `.select2-container` has `position: relative` but NO `z-index`. Without a `z-index`, it doesn't create a stacking context even though it has `position: relative`. Elements are stacked in DOM order.

But wait - with `position: relative` and NO z-index, elements are stacked in DOM order. 

Since `.label-flotante` comes after `.select2-container` in the DOM, it naturally appears on top, which is the correct behavior. The z-index fix I applied was actually unnecessary—adding `z-index: 1` to the label created its own stacking context, but the real issue is that `.select2-container` lacks one, so DOM order determines the layering anyway.

When the Select2 dropdown opens, a `.select2-close-mask` element gets inserted at the body level with `position: fixed; z-index: 99`, creating a semi-transparent overlay that captures clicks. Since `.label-flotante` is positioned absolutely within `.input-container`, the stacking context of that parent container becomes the key factor in determining whether the label sits above or below the dropdown mask. label's stacking context participation depends on whether there's a stacking context created by an ancestor.

Without any explicit stacking contexts in the chain, all positioned elements participate in the ROOT stacking context. In that case:
- `.select2-close-mask` (position: fixed, z-index: 99) is in root stacking context at z-index 99
- `.label-flotante` (position: absolute, z-index: auto) is in root stacking context at z-index auto (= 0)

So YES! The `.select2-close-mask` (z-index: 99) COVERS the `.label-flotante` (z-index: auto = 0) when the dropdown opens. This explains why the label appears to be "behind" when the dropdown opens.

But why doesn't the `z-index: 1` fix work? Because `z-index: 1` is still less than the close-mask's 99. The real solution is bumping the label's z-index above 99—something like 100 should do it. Though wait, the close-mask is actually transparent with `opacity: 0`, so even if it's layered on top, it shouldn't visually obscure anything. Let me reconsider what's actually happening here. I think I'm overcomplicating the z-index issue here. Looking at the actual DOM structure, the `#contenedor-select2-modals` div has a very high z-index of 10000 for modal dropdowns, but the main vista Select2 for `filtro_estado_tarea` doesn't specify a `dropdownParent`, so it appends directly to the body by default. Let me check the initialization code in inputs.js to see how these selects are actually being configured. I'm seeing there are actually two different select2 initializations happening—one for regular filters that disables search entirely, and another for filters with a search box enabled. The user set `buscador: true` expecting the search to work, but I need to check which initialization is being applied to `filtro_estado_tarea`. I'm realizing the close-mask might actually be blocking interaction even though it's supposed to be invisible—the CSS might only have the old IE filter for opacity without a modern `opacity` property, leaving it fully opaque with a white background. I'm realizing the close-mask being transparent doesn't actually explain why the label appears behind it visually. Let me reconsider the DOM structure—maybe the issue isn't about z-index or the close-mask at all, but rather how Select2 restructures the elements when it initializes.

Looking at the actual DOM, the `.select2-container` is positioned as a sibling to the label within the `.input-container`, and since the label uses `position: absolute` relative to that container, the stacking order depends on how these elements interact with the Select2 overlay.

